    "narrative": "For the Zurich Zebras on this April 8th slate, **Yordan Alvarez** anchors our lineup with an elite 82.97 projection, benefiting significantly from a favorable park environment (+14%) and an excellent spot in the two-hole against Lorenzen. He is closely trailed by **Trea Turner** (71.18) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (70.81). **Trea Turner** remains our premier engine for the scarce stolen base category, and despite a slight park penalty, his leadoff placement and favorable matchup against Mahle make him a lock. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** is a high-upside play against Boyle; even with pending lineups, his dynamic platoon advantage (+14%) justifies his status as a top-tier start. We are also looking for a breakout performance from **Colt Keith** (68.51); assuming he occupies the leadoff spot against Ober, the combination of wind assistance and an aggressive placement in the order provides a high floor for production.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Josh Smith**, who finished with a 41.35 score. While his platoon advantage against Woo (+14%) kept him in the conversation, the superior overall efficiency and situational context of our starting infield and outfield options relegated him to the bench. We continue to monitor the status of **Hyeseong Kim** and **Zac Veen**, the latter remaining in the minors and currently unusable for our scoring caps. Risks for today include the \"Lineup Pending\" designations for **Dillon Dingler**, **Colt Keith**, and **Pete Crow-Armstrong**; if these players shift down in their respective orders, their scores will compress. Additionally, **Christian Yelich** faces a stiff test against Gray\u2014the wind blowing in (-5%) and the opposing pitcher\u2019s skill (-17%) make him the most precarious of our high-upside plays. Should **Jerar Encarnacion** or **Logan O'Hoppe** struggle early, we are prepared to pivot to more efficient bench depth to preserve our game caps.",
